questiontext.text:
Magnetic flux

The magnitude of the magnetic flux density on the axis of a solenoid, as in the Figure below, can be found by the integral: \[B= \int_{\beta_1}^{\beta_2} \frac{\mu_0 n I}{2} \sin\beta \, \mathrm{d}\beta\] where \(\mu_0\) is the permeability of free space (\(\approx 4\pi\times 10^{-7} \mbox{Hm}^{-1}\)), \(n\) is the number of turns and \(I\) is the current.

Problem in words

Predict the magnetic flux in the middle of a long solenoid.

Mathematical statement of the problem

We assume that the solenoid is so long that \(\beta_1\approx 0\) and \(\beta_2\approx \pi\) so that \[B = {\displaystyle\int_{\beta_1}^{\beta_2}\dfrac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\sin \beta \, \mathrm{d}\beta}\approx {\displaystyle\int_0^{\pi}\dfrac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\sin\beta \, \mathrm{d}\beta}.\]

Mathematical analysis

The factor \(\dfrac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\) can be taken outside the integral, i.e. \[\begin{aligned} B &= \dfrac{\mu_0 n I}{2}{\displaystyle\int_0^{\pi}\sin\beta \, \mathrm{d}\beta} \\ &= \dfrac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\Bigg[ -\cos\beta\Bigg]_0^{\pi} \\ &=\dfrac{\mu_0 nI}{2}(-\cos\pi +\cos 0) \\ &=\dfrac{\mu_0 n I}{2}(-(-1)+1) = \mu_0 nI.\end{aligned}\]

Interpretation

The magnitude of the magnetic flux density at the midpoint of the axis of a long solenoid is predicted to be approximately \(\mu_0 nI\), i.e. proportional to the number of turns and proportional to the current flowing in the solenoid.
